#### Introduction
The "Dirty Pipe" vulnerability (CVE-2022-0847) is a critical security flaw in the Linux kernel that allows an unprivileged user to overwrite data in read-only files. This vulnerability can be exploited to escalate privileges and gain root access. The flaw is similar to the infamous "Dirty COW" vulnerability (CVE-2016-5195) but is easier to exploit. This guide will walk you through the process of writing code to exploit this vulnerability and explain how to use it.

#### Step-by-Step Guide

##### Step 1: Understanding the Vulnerability
The Dirty Pipe vulnerability arises from a flaw in the way the Linux kernel handles pipes. Specifically, it allows an attacker to inject data into the page cache of a read-only file, which can then be written to disk. This can be exploited to modify files that should be immutable, such as `/etc/passwd` or `/etc/shadow`.

##### Step 2: Setting Up the Environment
To exploit this vulnerability, you need a Linux system with a vulnerable kernel version. The affected versions are from 5.8 to 5.10.27 and 5.11 to 5.16.11. Ensure you have a non-root user account on this system.

##### Step 3: Writing the Exploit Code
The following code demonstrates how to exploit the Dirty Pipe vulnerability. This code will overwrite the root user's password in `/etc/passwd` to a known value, allowing you to log in as root.

```c
